g="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="734621"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018580-20180324-144303"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Insight</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">The Sunday Times says; Changi should be customer-friendly</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>There is instrumental logic in Changi Airport's decision to roll out penalties to unpunctual airlines. Both habitual latecomers and early birds end up disrupting schedules which inconveniences other users and could lead to unwanted costs. The proposed penalty is a fine of up to $100,000 and possible loss of a landing slot.</Para><Para>However, Changi should not make old-school fines and other punitive measures its default method for changing behaviour. In a competitive world, Changi has to put a premium on customer service and not appear high-handed.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Changi's operational efficiency is one of its main attractions, which have been recognised internationally again. It has been named the world's best airport, for the sixth consecutive year, by more than 13 million travellers who took part in a global survey. They evaluated their experiences across different aspects of operations - check-in, transfers, shopping, security and immigration processes. Naturally, they would form a different opinion if disruptive traffic schedules are routinely tolerated in the airport.</Para><Para>Airlines would also appreciate the need for operational discipline to serve travellers better. But the manner in which discipline is maintained by an airport is important. Incentives, for example, are often more effective to modify behaviour. As costs are a critical factor, airlines would make more efforts to be punctual when there are financial incentives for keeping strictly to schedules.</Para><Para>Airlines can in turn incentivise passengers in different ways to check in and board on time. The wrench in the works could be bad weather, technical glitches and the knock-on effect of delays at less-efficient airports in the region and beyond. With a greater emphasis on security in airports, heightened screening measures during uncertain periods could disrupt schedules too. Indeed, deciding the proximate causes of delay would be a challenge for airports. Hence the importance of using technology to work out optimal solutions when multiple difficulties arise. There's more to arriving and leaving on the dot than fines.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

